column1: Who will win the 2020 Nevada Democratic caucuses?
column6: ['US Politics', 'Elections and Referenda']
Nevada is a popular state for Joe Biden but white male Bernie Sanders has momentum and appeal.
All chips in for Bernie.

Biden's support continues to crumble, especially after a less than inspiring debate performance. Biden also tends to do worse than the poll projections, making a win in Nevada for win practically inconceivable.
Still hugging fivethirtyeight.com (and rounding).
New poll from Emerson College gives Sanders a 14 point lead. This pushes my prediction up a couple of points.
Nevada caucuses are only two days away, and Bernie has a double digit lead.
Looks like a lock for Bernie after yesterday's debate

I personally think the last debate will have a significant impact on the outcome of this primary. Because Elizabeth Warren came out “swinging” against Michael Bloomberg and I think she will see a rise in her numbers. Both Warren and “Mayor Pete” will see a significant rise in their numbers. Unfortunately, Amy Klobuchar will have the most negative impact from the last debate. I’m not sure if the list provided is correct so here is my predictions overall.

Following the abject failure of my monte carlo model for the iowa caucuses, I've made a new one for Nevada. This model is much more refined, but the fatal issue for my iowa model was not taking account of the rural/urban divide in different candidates' votes, given the weighting towards rural voters in the delegate process. If anyone has data on rural/urban divides in different candidates' supports, let me know.
Biden's NV debate performance, by all accounts, left it more unclear why voters should back him. "Being an alternative to Bernie" doesn't move the needle.

There have been three more polls since my last forecast which give Sanders an average lead of 6-7%. My model suggests this gives Sanders around a 70% chance of winning.

The failure of the Culinary Union to endorse any candidate is a blow to Biden - not to mention the recent Las Vegas Review-Journal polling putting him in second place to Bernie. In my readings, I found an assertion that Biden has never won a presidential primary - and that seems to be true. There is nothing that I see where NV 2020 will be the first win for Biden. Open field running for Bernie at this point.. I gave zero chance for a Mike Bloomberg surprise b/c I found NV law does now allow write-ins. While not entirely sure about this prohibition for caucuses - as they are private party affairs - I figure they must follow state rules and voted accordingly.

The momentum Bernie is gaining with pledged endorsements from an impressive list of organizations (not to mention polls, individual donations and huge rallies) feels like a solid indicator that Bernie has the strongest shot at Nevada, and possibly beyond.

The latest poll in this state gives Sanders a 7 point lead over Joe Biden. My model suggests this translates to a 65% chance of Sanders winning the nomination for this state. I'm going to downgrade to 60% though as the polls in Iowa and New Hampshire seem to have overestimated Sanders popularity and underestimated Buttigieg's.

Biden and Sanders should both do well here, with Biden having an edge with minorities and Sanders perhaps with an edge among union voters. Buttigieg, Bloomberg and Klobuchar will split the remainder of the centrist vote, Steyer will have some name recognition there, but not enough to make a difference, and Warren will lose out on the liberal vote to Sanders.
Bloomberg will finally get more recognition.
Mike Bloomberg. I believe he has the ideas and forethought to gather the strength of voters that he needs.

Adjusting to brace for Nevada's uncertainty and historic unpredictability (e.g. major groups supporting one candidate and flipping when it comes time to vote.) Biden is on the edge of momentum that could tip in either direction. Support for Sanders is a major uncertainty.
538 says Sanders up and Biden down.
In the absence of a Culinary Workers' Union endorsement, I'm back up on Sanders.

The Culinary Workers Union, which is the largest union in Nevada, is not endorsing anyone as of today [1] - though note that the union leadership has clearly expressed its opposition to Sanders and his medicare-for-all plan [2].

The Culinary Workers' Union leadership is holding a press conference in Las Vegas in about 45 minutes. It will be interesting to see if they endorse a candidate. Whoever picks up their endorsement will have a very sophisticated organization backing them.
Based on FiveThirtyEight's forecast, adjusting to give higher probabilities to the two main contenders.

8 runners give everyone a start of 12.5% random pick chance. From there we can see where the momentum has been flowing PB + BS - JB- EW - AK+. We can then take into account polling number averages and the potential Bloomberg effect. Add time until Saturday, and we have a race between PB, BS and JB.
Amy will take it. Most centrist of all Democrats.
Mayor Pete or Klobachar have real chances here.
Most Dems from Nevada are quite young and recent transplants.

The polls say Biden but momentum says Sanders. Polls can be misleading though, because I wonder how many people fear the stigma of claiming to vote for a "democratic socialist." Biden is having difficulty staying on message, question is, does the white, rural vote see him as a viable challenger to Trump. Warren appears to be retreating in NV and SC to live to fight another state... either showing confidence or frugality.

The Culinary Union has attacked Sanders' Medicare-for-All proposal. Ordinarily something like this might not matter much, but Nevada is a caucus state, and organization counts. Buttigieg is on record as being against Medicare-for-All, so I suppose it's possible he can edge out Sanders by a delegate or two, as he did in Iowa.
warren may have a chance to show her organizational skills
Bernie Sanders has gotten the most votes out of the two races thus far. His base is loyal, and the rest of the field seems fragmented.

Taking the results of the 2020 Iowa caucus by demographic group, Bernie Sanders appears poised to win Nevada if he carries similar percentages as in Iowa. According to the U.S. census, Nevada's slightly younger, less educated, and significantly more Hispanic population all favors Sanders. Coming out of Iowa, Sanders' main rival is Pete Buttigieg ("someone else" in this forecast), but his poor showing among Hispanic Iowans does not bode well for his chances in Nevada. Joe Biden, another potential rival to Sander's in Nevada is leading in the polls, but there has not been a new poll in almost a month. Biden did terribly in Iowa and looks to do even worse in New Hampshire. He will have no momentum and dwindling money going into Nevada. Sanders barely lost Nevada in 2016. https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2020/president/nv/nevada_democratic_presidential_caucus-6866.html https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/IA,NV/PST045219 https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/02/03/us/elections/results-iowa-caucus-polls.html https://www.cnn.com/election/2016/primaries/polls/nv/Dem

Slow Joe seems tired.

In the 14 primary polls compiled on Wikipedia since Biden announces his candidacy in April of last year, Joe Biden leads in 11 of them, with Bernie Sanders within a few % each time while leading in two of the polls, the last and most recent poll going to "undecided". Sanders has slowly been gaining as Biden's polling has been dropping. As of now it seems that Sanders will win Iowa, but if polling is to be trusted, Biden will win by a slight margin unless Sanders' victory in Iowa is enough of a push to turn the moderates toward the left.

FiveThirtyEight polls currently have Biden leading, but that may drop after the Iowa caucus results, the polls for which had Sanders leading slightly, which may lower Biden's chances slightly. Additionally, because Warren has dropped steadily over the past month in polls her chances may lessen as the month continues. Steyer and Buttigieg do not have enough momentum in the polls to counter Sanders or Biden. Lastly, in the 2016 election, Sanders slowly caught up to Clinton and the final polls had Sanders with considerable support.
https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2020-primary-forecast/nevada/

Polling trends show Bernie narrowly winning Iowa and solidly taking New Hampshire, the first two states. Biden has the softest support among voters, who may move away from him if he loses the first two states. Biden's supporters second choice is split between Bernie and Warren. If Biden pulls through in Iowa, he has a decent shot at taking Nevada, but it's a union-heavy state with high Latino population which bodes well for Bernie.
Following the assessment of fivethirtyeight.com
Hillary won Nevada in 2016, 52.64% to Bernie's 47.29%. Current polls show Biden 24.2%, Sanders 22.4%, Warren 13.5%.
